<subSubSection pageId="102" pageNumber="103" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="102.[151,1437,282,1278]" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1182,1207]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="102" pageNumber="103" reason="1">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Muir" authorityName="Muir" authorityYear="1926" box="[330,637,1182,1206]" class="Insecta" family="Derbidae" genus="Rhotana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="102" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="semiopalina">
<emphasis box="[330,571,1182,1206]" italics="true" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Rhotana semiopalina</emphasis>
Muir
</taxonomicName>
can be easily recognized by two distinct characters: (1) the dark and narrow infuscation lining the apical cross-veins on the forewings, and (2) the elongated, triangular-shaped outline of the male genital styles.
